WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:06.264
Myasthenia gravis is a neuromuscular
disease that directly impacts respiratory function,

2
00:00:06.965 --> 00:00:10.364
making it critical for respiratory
therapists to recognize early.

3
00:00:11.064 --> 00:00:14.225
At its core, this condition is caused by
an autoimmune

4
00:00:14.225 --> 00:00:17.844
attack on acetylcholine receptors at the
neuromuscular junction.

5
00:00:18.825 --> 00:00:22.825
This blocks normal communication between
nerves and muscles, leading to

6
00:00:22.825 --> 00:00:26.405
muscle weakness that worsens with activity
and improves with rest.

7
00:00:26.604 --> 00:00:30.864
From an RT perspective, the biggest
concern is respiratory muscle

8
00:00:30.864 --> 00:00:31.565
involvement.

9
00:00:32.444 --> 00:00:36.244
Patients may initially present with subtle
signs like ptosis, diplopia,

10
00:00:36.465 --> 00:00:40.485
or difficulty chewing and swallowing, but
as the disease progresses,

11
00:00:41.125 --> 00:00:45.125
weakness can affect the diaphragm and
intercostal muscles, leading to

12
00:00:45.125 --> 00:00:47.205
hypoventilation and respiratory failure.

13
00:00:48.185 --> 00:00:53.544
Pathophysiologically, fewer functional
receptors mean reduced muscle contraction strength.

14
00:00:53.884 --> 00:00:58.005
Over time, repeated use leads to fatigue
because the available

15
00:00:58.005 --> 00:01:00.625
receptors cannot sustain muscle
activation.

16
00:01:01.384 --> 00:01:04.885
This is why symptoms worsen throughout the
day or with repeated effort.

17
00:01:05.705 --> 00:01:09.745
Diagnostics often include antibody
testing, edrophonium testing,

18
00:01:10.125 --> 00:01:12.205
and pulmonary function monitoring.

19
00:01:12.264 --> 00:01:17.144
Key respiratory metrics include vital
capacity and negative inspiratory force.

20
00:01:17.144 --> 00:01:22.364
A declining vital capacity, especially
below 15 mL per kg

21
00:01:22.364 --> 00:01:26.105
or a weak NIF, is a major red flag for

22
00:01:26.105 --> 00:01:27.605
impending respiratory failure.

23
00:01:28.444 --> 00:01:33.504
One of the most important distinctions is
between a myasthenic crisis and a cholinergic

24
00:01:33.504 --> 00:01:34.084
crisis.

25
00:01:34.245 --> 00:01:40.544
A myasthenic crisis is due to too little
acetylcholine activity and requires increased support,

26
00:01:40.964 --> 00:01:42.845
often including ventilatory assistance.

27
00:01:43.205 --> 00:01:45.364
A cholinergic crisis, on the other hand,

28
00:01:45.745 --> 00:01:49.444
is caused by too much acetylcholine,
typically from over-medication,

29
00:01:49.764 --> 00:01:52.785
and presents with increased secretions and
bradycardia.

30
00:01:54.065 --> 00:01:56.605
Management focuses on maintaining airway,
breathing,

31
00:01:56.684 --> 00:01:57.504
and ventilation.

32
00:01:58.224 --> 00:02:02.004
Non-invasive support may be appropriate
early, but intubation should

33
00:02:02.004 --> 00:02:06.605
not be delayed if the patient shows signs
of fatigue or deteriorating gas exchange.

34
00:02:07.245 --> 00:02:12.384
Medications include anticholinesterase
agents, corticosteroids, and

35
00:02:12.384 --> 00:02:13.365
immunosuppressants.

36
00:02:14.005 --> 00:02:17.464
For respiratory therapists, continuous
monitoring is essential.

37
00:02:18.625 --> 00:02:21.604
Watch for decreasing tidal volume, rising
CO2,

38
00:02:22.184 --> 00:02:25.065
increasing work of breathing, and changes
in mental status.

39
00:02:25.585 --> 00:02:27.304
These are signs the patient is failing.

40
00:02:27.964 --> 00:02:29.964
The key takeaway is this.

41
00:02:30.324 --> 00:02:33.085
Myasthenia gravis is not just a muscle
disease.

42
00:02:33.085 --> 00:02:35.845
It's a ventilation problem waiting to
happen.

43
00:02:36.725 --> 00:02:39.664
Early recognition, careful monitoring, and
timely

44
00:02:39.664 --> 00:02:43.544
intervention can prevent rapid
deterioration and save lives.

